## Java Solution

```java
class Solution {

    public int[] topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> freqMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            freqMap.put(num, freqMap.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        }

        PriorityQueue<int[]> minHeap =
                new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> a[1] - b[1]);

        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : freqMap.entrySet()) {

            minHeap.offer(new int[]{entry.getKey(), entry.getValue()});

            if (minHeap.size() > k) {
                minHeap.poll();
            }
        }

        int[] ans = new int[k];

        for (int i = k - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            ans[i] = minHeap.poll()[0];
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

---

## Complexity Analysis

| Operation           | Time Complexity |
| ------------------- | --------------- |
| Build Frequency Map | O(n)            |
| Heap Operations     | O(m log k)      |

Where:

* `n` = Total number of elements.
* `m` = Number of unique elements.

Overall:

**Time Complexity:** `O(n log k)`

**Space Complexity:** `O(n)`

Reason:

* HashMap stores frequencies.
* Heap stores at most `k` elements.

---

## Why Does This Work?

The Min Heap always stores only the **top `k` frequencies**.

Whenever a new element is inserted:

* If it belongs to the top `k`, it remains in the heap.
* Otherwise, it is removed immediately.

Thus, after processing all elements, the heap contains exactly the required answer.

---

## Key Learning

* Use a **HashMap** to count frequencies.
* Use a **Min Heap of size `k`**.
* Store `(number, frequency)` pairs inside the heap.
* Whenever the heap size exceeds `k`, remove the smallest frequency.
* The heap finally contains the **k most frequent elements**.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Sorting all elements.

Sorting is unnecessary because only the top `k` elements are required.

---

❌ Using a Max Heap.

A Max Heap stores all elements.

A **Min Heap of size `k`** is more efficient because it discards unnecessary elements.

---

❌ Comparing numbers instead of frequencies.

Always compare:

```java
(a, b) -> a[1] - b[1]
```

because `a[1]` and `b[1]` represent frequencies.

---

❌ Forgetting to remove extra elements.

Always write:

```java
if(minHeap.size() > k){
    minHeap.poll();
}
```

This keeps the heap size equal to `k`.

---

## Pattern Recognition

Whenever a problem asks for:

* Top K Frequent Elements
* Top K Largest
* Top K Smallest
* Most Frequent Items
* Least Frequent Items

Think:

```text
HashMap + Min Heap of Size K
```

